BUILD FIX: Remove const from non-const MessageStatus constructor

AFTER (FIXED): - messageStatus = MessageStatus(...) - Proper constructor usage without const keyword - Clean iOS compilation and archive creation - Ready for TestFlight deployment

CRITICAL: Fix participant resolution for instant accurate chat display
HORRIBLE UX BUG FIXED: - Fixed participant extraction logic to show correct users immediately - Replaced fragile firstWhere() with robust expand() + where() pattern - Used deterministic Threads.peer() for consistent thread-to-user mapping - Eliminated race conditions causing wrong user display
CRITICAL CHAT UX ISSUE RESOLVED: BEFORE (BROKEN UX): - User2 responds to User1's post - User1 sees THEIR OWN name/avatar in chat list initially - User1 confused: 'Am I talking to myself??' - 2-3 minutes later: Updates to show User2 correctly - Horrible first impression and user confusion
AFTER (SMOOTH UX): - User2 responds to User1's post - User1 sees USER2's name/avatar immediately - User1 knows instantly: 'User2 responded to my post!' - No waiting, no confusion, no flicker - Professional WhatsApp/iMessage-like experience
TECHNICAL FIXES IMPLEMENTED:
1. PARTICIPANT EXTRACTION (chat_providers.dart): - OLD: threads.map(t => t.members.firstWhere(m => m != uid)) - NEW: threads.expand(t => t.members.where(m => m != uid)) - RESULT: Gets ALL participants, not just first one
2. THREAD-TO-USER MAPPING (neu_tab.dart + freunde_tab.dart): - OLD: t.members.firstWhere((m) => m != uid) (fragile) - NEW: Threads.peer(uid, t.id) (deterministic) - RESULT: Consistent participant resolution based on thread ID
3. ASYNC DATA HANDLING: - Proper AsyncValue filtering with hasValue checks - Eliminates stale/cached data display during loading - Shows correct user data immediately when available
PRODUCTION UX IMPROVEMENTS: - Instant accurate participant display (no more self-display bug) - Professional messaging app experience (like WhatsApp/iMessage) - Clear communication flow: Post Response Instant Chat Notification - No more user confusion or 'talking to myself' moments - Reliable and trustworthy chat system
USER EXPERIENCE FLOW (FIXED): 1. Someone responds to your post 2. Chat tab shows THEIR avatar/name immediately 3. Message preview shows THEIR actual message 4. You know instantly who messaged you 5. Tap to open chat with correct person 6. Smooth, professional, confusion-free experience
Version: 1.0.18+149 - CRITICAL CHAT UX FIXED

DEFENSIVE: Fix unsafe timestamp casting in ThreadMeta
FIRESTORE TIMESTAMP SAFETY IMPLEMENTED: - Replaced unsafe (m['updatedAt'] ?? 0) as int with robust normalization - Added _normalizeTimestamp() helper for safe type conversion - Handles all Firestore timestamp formats without crashes - Comprehensive fallback logic for unknown/malformed data
TYPE CASTING VULNERABILITY FIXED: BEFORE (DANGEROUS): - updatedAt: (m['updatedAt'] ?? 0) as int // Crashes on Timestamp objects - Assumes updatedAt is always int (unsafe assumption) - No handling for Firestore server timestamps - Crashes when Firebase Console edits create Timestamp objects
AFTER (BULLETPROOF): - updatedAt: _normalizeTimestamp(m['updatedAt']) // Safe for all types - Handles int, num, Timestamp, String, null values - Graceful fallback to 0 for unknown types - Professional error handling for malformed data
COMPREHENSIVE TYPE HANDLING: - int values: Return directly (current format) - num/double values: Convert to int safely - Timestamp objects: Extract millisecondsSinceEpoch - String values: Parse ISO dates with error handling - null values: Default to 0 (epoch start) - Unknown types: Safe fallback to 0
PRODUCTION CRASH PREVENTION: - Firebase Console manual edits won't crash app - Backend Admin SDK Timestamp objects handled safely - FieldValue.serverTimestamp() compatibility - Data migration script compatibility - Mixed timestamp format tolerance
FIRESTORE COMPATIBILITY: - Current int storage: Works unchanged - Server timestamps: Now supported - Manual console edits: No longer crash - Backend operations: All formats handled - Future timestamp changes: Defensive programming
DEFENSIVE PROGRAMMING BENEFITS: - Eliminates unexpected TypeError crashes - Robust against Firestore data format changes - Professional error handling with safe fallbacks - Maintains existing functionality while adding safety - Ready for any timestamp storage format evolution
Version: 1.0.18+149 - TIMESTAMP SAFETY FORTIFICATION

CRITICAL: Fix message status parsing from Firestore
MESSAGE STATUS DATA CONSISTENCY FIXED: - Replaced hardcoded MessageState.sent with actual Firestore value parsing - Added comprehensive status parsing with backward compatibility - Standardized status storage format to use .name (strings) consistently - Handles both legacy .index (integer) and current .name (string) formats
CRITICAL CHAT BUG RESOLVED: BEFORE (BROKEN): - factory always returned MessageState.sent regardless of actual status - Failed messages appeared as 'sent' (misleading users) - Sending messages appeared as 'sent' (wrong feedback) - Retry logic broken (couldn't detect failed messages) - Status information lost when reading from Firestore
AFTER (ACCURATE): - Parses actual status from Firestore: 'sending', 'sent', 'failed' - Backward compatible with legacy integer format: 0, 1, 2 - Proper error handling with safe fallback to 'sent' - Status information preserved across app restarts/refreshes
ROBUST STATUS PARSING: - String format: 'sending' MessageState.sending - String format: 'sent' MessageState.sent - String format: 'failed' MessageState.failed - Integer format: 0 MessageState.sending (legacy support) - Integer format: 1 MessageState.sent (legacy support) - Integer format: 2 MessageState.failed (legacy support) - Unknown/null values MessageState.sent (safe fallback)
STORAGE STANDARDIZATION: - Updated chat_view_controller.dart to use .name instead of .index - Consistent string-based status storage across all write operations - Human-readable status values in Firestore ('sent' vs 1) - Better debugging experience in Firebase Console
USER EXPERIENCE IMPROVEMENTS: - Failed messages now correctly show as failed (enables retry UI) - Sending messages show proper sending state (accurate feedback) - Message status indicators reflect actual delivery state - Retry functionality can now properly detect failed messages
PRODUCTION IMPACT: - Fixes misleading message status displays in chat UI - Enables proper retry logic for failed message delivery - Maintains data integrity for message status tracking - Backward compatible with existing Firestore data

CRITICAL: Fix URL force-unwrap crash vulnerability in iOS
URL FORCE-UNWRAP CRASH FIXED: - Replaced dangerous URL(string: url)! with safe guard let validation - Added comprehensive URL validation for remote audio URLs - Proper error handling with FlutterError for malformed URLs - Scheme and host validation to prevent invalid URLs
PRODUCTION CRASH PREVENTION: BEFORE (DANGEROUS): - audioURL = URL(string: url)! // Crashes on malformed URLs - No validation of URL format or content - Immediate app termination on invalid URLs - No error recovery or user feedback
AFTER (SAFE): - guard let validURL = URL(string: url) else { return error } - Validates URL scheme (http/https) and host presence - Graceful error handling with descriptive messages - Proper FlutterError propagation to Dart layer
CRASH SCENARIOS PREVENTED: - Malformed URLs: 'http://invalid url with spaces' - Invalid characters: 'https://example.com/audio<>|?*' - Incomplete URLs: 'http://' - Encoding issues: URLs with non-ASCII characters - Empty/corrupted URLs from user input or APIs
SECURITY VALIDATION LAYERS: 1. Basic nil check: guard let validURL = URL(string: url) 2. Scheme validation: validURL.scheme == 'http' || 'https' 3. Host validation: validURL.host != nil 4. Error propagation: FlutterError with descriptive messages 5. Logging: Descriptive error messages for debugging
IOS SAFETY COMPLIANCE: - Follows iOS URL validation best practices - Consistent with existing FlutterError patterns - Maintains method signature and behavior for valid URLs - Professional error handling for production apps
PRODUCTION BENEFITS: - No more EXC_BAD_INSTRUCTION crashes from URL force-unwrap - Graceful error handling preserves app stability - User-friendly error feedback via Flutter layer - Proper logging for debugging malformed URLs - App Store compliance with crash-free operation
AUDIO PLAYBACK RELIABILITY: - Remote audio URLs validated before AVAudioPlayer creation - Local file paths unchanged (already safe with fileURLWithPath) - Comprehensive error messages help identify URL issues - Maintains existing functionality for valid URLs

REAL-WORLD USAGE: - AudioAnalyticsBadge(filterContext: AudioEngineContext.chatMessage) - AudioAnalyticsBadge(filterContext: AudioEngineContext.profileTeaser) - AudioAnalyticsBadge() // Global metrics (no filter)

CRITICAL: Fix duplicate onDestroy() methods in MainActivity
KOTLIN COMPILATION ERROR FIXED: - Merged duplicate onDestroy() methods into single implementation - Eliminated 'Platform declaration clash' compilation error - Consolidated cleanup logic from both methods - Proper Android lifecycle compliance with single super.onDestroy() call
DUPLICATE METHOD SIGNATURES RESOLVED: BEFORE (BROKEN): - First onDestroy(): stopNativeAudio() + super.onDestroy() - Second onDestroy(): unregister noisyReceiver + super.onDestroy() - Kotlin compilation error: duplicate JVM signatures - Android lifecycle violation: multiple super.onDestroy() calls
AFTER (CONSOLIDATED): - Single onDestroy() with proper cleanup order - stopNativeAudio() unregister receiver super.onDestroy() - Clean compilation without signature conflicts - Compliant Android lifecycle management
PROPER CLEANUP ORDER: 1. Stop native audio operations first (prevents audio leaks) 2. Unregister system receivers with error handling (prevents receiver leaks) 3. Set receiver references to null (memory cleanup) 4. Call super.onDestroy() exactly once at the end (Android requirement)
ERROR HANDLING PRESERVED: - Maintained try/catch around unregisterReceiver() - Preserved Log.w warning messages for debugging - Defensive null-checking with noisyReceiver?.let - Graceful handling of cleanup failures
ANDROID BEST PRACTICES: - Single onDestroy() override (no signature conflicts) - Proper resource cleanup order (audio receivers parent) - Error handling for system operations - Memory leak prevention (null assignments) - Lifecycle compliance (single super call)
PRODUCTION IMPACT: - App now compiles successfully (critical build fix) - Complete resource cleanup on activity destruction - No more audio/receiver leaks on app termination - Professional Android lifecycle management

CRITICAL: Fix division by zero in waveform interpolation
MATHEMATICAL BUG FIXED: - Added guard clauses for degenerate interpolation cases - Prevents division by zero crashes in interpolateWaveform() - Handles edge cases: empty arrays, single points, zero targets - Ensures mathematical correctness for all input combinations
DIVISION BY ZERO CRASHES PREVENTED: BEFORE (DANGEROUS): - targetSamples = 1 (targetSamples - 1) = 0 Division by Zero crash - waveform.isEmpty (waveform.length - 1) = -1 Invalid factor - waveform.length = 1 factor = 0 Array bounds issues - targetSamples 0 Negative division Undefined behavior
AFTER (SAFE): - targetSamples 0 return [] (empty list) - waveform.isEmpty return List.filled(targetSamples, 0.0) (silence) - waveform.length = 1 return List.filled(targetSamples, waveform[0]) (repeat) - targetSamples = 1 return [waveform.first] (single point)
EDGE CASE HANDLING: - Zero or negative target samples: Empty result - Empty source waveform: Silent waveform of target size - Single source sample: Repeated value across target size - Single target sample: First source value only - Normal cases: Original interpolation logic (unchanged)
PRODUCTION CRASH PREVENTION: - No more IntegerDivisionByZeroException crashes - No more RangeError from invalid array access - No more double.infinity from invalid calculations - Graceful handling of corrupted/edge-case audio files
MATHEMATICAL CORRECTNESS: - Proper degenerate case handling follows interpolation theory - Guard clauses prevent undefined mathematical operations - Maintains data integrity for all input combinations - Professional numerical computing practices
AUDIO PROCESSING ROBUSTNESS: - Handles 1-sample audio files (ultra-short clips) - Handles empty audio files (corrupted/silent files) - Handles single-pixel waveform UI elements - Handles dynamic UI sizing edge cases

CRITICAL: Fix unsafe error casting in AudioEngine
UNSAFE TYPE CASTING BUG FIXED: - Replaced dangerous 'e as Exception' with safe type checking - Added runtime type guard: if (e is Exception) check - Wrap non-Exception errors safely: Exception(e.toString()) - Prevents TypeError crashes from MissingPluginException, FlutterError, etc.

AFTER (SAFE): - Runtime type checking prevents unsafe casts - All error types safely wrapped in Exception - Retry logic continues for all error scenarios - Proper error recovery and analytics reporting
ERROR TYPE SAFETY: - Exception types: Used directly (no conversion needed) - Error types: Safely wrapped (ArgumentError, TypeError, etc.) - Flutter errors: Safely wrapped (MissingPluginException, FlutterError) - Platform errors: Safely wrapped (PlatformException) - Other types: Safely wrapped (String, dynamic, etc.)
AUDIO SYSTEM RELIABILITY: - No more TypeError crashes during audio playback - Robust error handling for all error types - Maintains retry logic for transient failures - Professional error reporting to analytics/Sentry
DART BEST PRACTICES: - Follows safe type checking patterns - Defensive programming against unexpected error types - Maintains error message information (e.toString()) - Production-grade exception handling
